<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="126" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,151,464]" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,295,320]" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Male with epandrium and surstyli distinctly bulb-shaped (posterior view) (
<figureCitation box="[1237,1330,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1028]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1034]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epandrium and surstyli (posterior view) of Bactrocera and Dacus. (A) B. (Tetradacus) minax; (B), D. (Callantra) longicornis; (C) D. (Didacus) ciliatus; (D) D. (Leptoxyda) persicus; (E) D. (Mellesis) crabroniformis; (F) D. (Mellesis) discophorus; (G) D. (Mellesis) ramanii; (H) D. (Neodacus) sphaeroidalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622652/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">Fig. 7F</figureCitation>
). Lateral surstylus shorter than epandrium, apex of posterior lobe of surstylus lanceolate, 2Ì„3 times longer than anterior lobe (
<figureCitation box="[159,248,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1516,1538]" captionTargetBox="[207,1424,195,1478]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,193,1481]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Epandrium and surstyli (lateral view) of tribe Dacini. (A) Z. (Parasinodacus) incisus; (B) B. (Parazeugodacus) bipustulata; (C) Z. (Zeugodacus) assamensis; (D) Z. (Z.) caudatus; (E) Z. (Z.) cucurbitae; (F) Z. (Z.) fuscoalatus; (G) Z. (Z.) gavisus; (H) Z. (Z.) havelockiae; (I) Z. (Z.) scutellaris; (J) Z. (Z.) tau; (K) Z. (Z.) watersi; (L) Z. (Z.) zahadi; (M) B. (Tetradacus) minax; (N) Dacus (Callantra) longicornis; (O) D. (Didacus) ciliatus; (P) D. (Leptoxyda) persicus; (Q) D. (Mellesis) crabroniformis; (R) D. (M.) discophorus; (S) D. (M.) ramanii; (T) D. (Neodacus) sphaeroidalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622645/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">Fig. 4R</figureCitation>
). Proctiger triangular and smaller than epandrium. Medial surstylus longer than lateral surstylus, tapering towards apex with a pair of prensisetae (
<figureCitation box="[613,700,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1028]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,193,1034]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epandrium and surstyli (posterior view) of Bactrocera and Dacus. (A) B. (Tetradacus) minax; (B), D. (Callantra) longicornis; (C) D. (Didacus) ciliatus; (D) D. (Leptoxyda) persicus; (E) D. (Mellesis) crabroniformis; (F) D. (Mellesis) discophorus; (G) D. (Mellesis) ramanii; (H) D. (Neodacus) sphaeroidalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622652/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">Fig. 7F</figureCitation>
). Phallus 
<quantity box="[812,899,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="25" pageNumber="126" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
long excluding glans (
<quantity box="[1160,1267,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="25" pageNumber="126" unit="mm" value="0.38">0.38 mm</quantity>
); 0.75 of glans sclerotised with (hexagonal) patterned praeputium; subapical lobe and basal lobe present (
<figureCitation box="[1160,1260,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1732,1754]" captionTargetBox="[160,1404,195,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[160,1445,195,1692]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Glans of phallus of Dacini. (A) Z. (Zeugodacus) assamensis; (B) Z. (Z.) caudatus; (C) B. (Z.) cucurbitae; (D) Z. (Z.) fuscoalatus; (E) Z. (Z.) gavisus; (F) Z. (Z.) havelockiae; (G) Z. (Z.) scutellaris; (H) Z.(Z.) tau; (I) Z. (Z.) watersi; (J) Z. (Z.) zahadi; (K) B. (Tetradacus) minax; (L) Dacus (Callantra) longicornis; (M) D. (Didacus) ciliatus; (N) D. (Leptoxyda) persicus; (O) D. (Mellesis) crabroniformis; (P) D. (M.) discophorus; (Q) D. (M.) ramanii; (R) D. (Neodacus) sphaeroidalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622658/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="126">Fig. 10P</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
